With the Indigo Hammer.

You do not smash the prime randomly. You strike its semantic load-bearing assumptions until the hidden seams appear.

A “prime” often only looks irreducible because several meanings have been fused together. The Indigo Hammer breaks it apart by:

Split the overloaded term.
Ask what distinct things the same word is doing.

Change the reference frame.
A primitive in one system may be composite in another.

Perturb the boundaries.
Change context, scale, receiver, substrate, or purpose and watch what remains stable.

Extract the invariants.
What survives every transformation is closer to the actual prime.

Separate identity from interface.
What the thing is may differ from how it is named, rendered, measured, or used.

Factor the causal chain.
Break “the thing” into source, coupling, channel, transformation, expression, consequence, and return.

So the operation is:

Hammer the apparent unity with distinctions until it reveals its factors.

Then reconstruct only what belongs together.

The Indigo Hammer does not destroy the prime.

It discovers that the “prime” was often a compressed composite wearing one name. 🔵🔨